    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <dateline>
                    <date when="1818-02-08"> </date></dateline>
                      
                      <p>
                     SundayFeb.y 8th 1818<lb/>
                               <note>8</note><lb/>
                       
                       Miss Baillie’s letter will not<lb/> 
                          be quite intelligible to you <lb/>
                          my dear Aunt without a<lb/>
                          note from ME.—You must<lb/> 
                          know that just after you<lb/> 
                          left Dublin there appeared<lb/> 
                          in some Dublin paper a let-<lb/>
                          ter taken from a Scotch paper<lb/>
                          called the Craftsman con-<lb/>
                          taining a sort of critique<lb/> 
                          or comparision between the<lb/> 
                          novels of miss E and of the<lb/> 
                          author of Waverley &amp;c—I [deletion]was[/deletion]<lb/> 
                          believing as I always have<lb/> 
                          done that Walter Scott if<lb/> 
                          not the sole author at<lb/> 
                       
                       <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page02.jpg"/>
                          least the directing soul of those<lb/> 
                          works, and being really<lb/>
                          fond of him &amp; grateful for<lb/> 
                          his kindness to me was<lb/> 
                          particularly vexed to see<lb/>
                          this insidious compari<lb/>
                          son instituted between us<lb/>
                          for in the course of the  de-<lb/>
                          fence of miss E which this<lb/> 
                          purported to be many things<lb/> 
                          were said about him in<lb/>
                          which I should be very sorry<lb/>
                          he could think that under<lb/>
                          hand or any way I had<lb/> 
                          any concern—I wrote to<lb/> 
                          my friend Joanna express-<lb/>
                          ing these feelings—<lb/> </p>
                       
                       <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page03.jpg"/>
                          <p>
                          Now the first part of her<lb/> 
                          letter will be intelligence<lb/> 
                          but you will come to a story<lb/> 
                          about Sir Alexr Gordon whh<lb/>
                          requires an explanatory<lb/> 
                          preface—<lb/> </p>
                
                         <p>
                          All Dublin you know was talk<lb/>
                          ing over the long canvassed<lb/> 
                          question Is W. Scott or not the<lb/> 
                          author of the 3 unclaimed<lb/>
                          novels?— Now one of the Miss<lb/> 
                          Hamilton’s told Harriet B<lb/>
                          who told me the following<lb/>
                          anecdote.<lb/> </p>
                
                          <p>
                          That Sir Alex Gordon had<lb/> 
                          declared to her his conviction<lb/> 
                          of W. Scott being the author<lb/> 
                          because before the publica<lb/>
                          tion of Guy Mannering he<lb/> 
                          the said Sir Alexr went<lb/>
                       
                       <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_717_1818-02-08_page04.jpg"/>
                          to one of his tenants houses<lb/>
                          where he met W. Scott &amp; where<lb/> 
                          first such a scene passed as is<lb/> 
                          painted in Guy Mannering<lb/>
                          at the funeral of [unclear]Steeney[/unclear]—<lb/> 
                          The said Sir Alexr further<lb/>
                          declared that when he again<lb/>
                          met Walter Scott after the pub<lb/>
                          lication of Guy Mannering<lb/>
                          &amp; reminded him or was<lb/> 
                          going to remind him of<lb/> 
                          this circumstance Walter<lb/>
                          Scott put his finger on his<lb/> 
                          lips in token of silence<lb/> 
                          &amp; secrecy—<lb/> </p>
                
                          <p>
                          It appears you will see<lb/> 
                          that the knight would<lb/> 
                          have done better to be silent<lb/>
                          </p>
                
                         <closer> 
                          Ys affectionately<lb/> 
                          Maria Edgeworth<lb/>
                        </closer>
                                
            </div>
